## Rust + Swift (XCFramework) bridge

This project pairs a Rust core/adapters/ffi workspace at `core/`
with a SwiftUI Xcode app at `app/`. The bridge is generated by
`uniffi` and packaged as an XCFramework consumed by Xcode.

**Layout**

- `core/crates/core/` — pure Rust logic.
- `core/crates/adapters/` — I/O wrappers (Rust side).
- `core/crates/ffi/` — uniffi-exposed Swift API. **All Swift-facing functions live here.** Keep this crate thin — only marshalling.
- `core/crates/ffi/src/core.udl` — the Swift-facing interface declaration.
- `app/Sources/Trilithon/Generated/` — uniffi-generated Swift bindings (regenerated by `just build-core`; do not hand-edit).

**Workflow**

- Edit Rust core/adapters as normal.
- Add a Swift-facing function: declare it in `core.udl`, implement it in `crates/ffi/src/lib.rs`, run `just build-core`.
- Run `just sync-bindings` if you changed the `.udl` (refreshes the Swift wrapper files).
- See `app/XCFRAMEWORK_INTEGRATION.txt` for one-time Xcode setup.

**Discipline**

- The `ffi` crate is the only place Swift can call into. Keep it thin.
- Don't expose Rust types directly — translate at the FFI boundary.
- Rebuild the XCFramework before pushing changes that affect the Swift API.
